Airbnb visualization¶

By Danilo Motta

In this project I intend to analyse the data Airbnb data and find some business opportunities to improve the experience for Airbnb costumers and increase profitability.

First lets start with some data exploration and visualization.

The data used in this project was made availabe online by Inside Airbnb.

Review distribution¶

Lets check the reviews distribution to compare the selected cities.

In [6]:
df['review_scores_rating_10'] = df.review_scores_rating // 10

rev_cols = ['review_scores_rating_10',
            'review_scores_accuracy',
            'review_scores_cleanliness',
            'review_scores_checkin',
            'review_scores_communication',
            'review_scores_location',
            'review_scores_value']

for col in rev_cols:        
    counts = df.groupby(['city'])[col] \
                .value_counts(normalize=True) \
                .rename('percentage') \
                .mul(100) \
                .reset_index() \
                .sort_values('percentage')

    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
    plt.title(col+' distribution by country')
    sns.barplot(x=col, y="percentage", hue='city', data=counts, hue_order=cities)
    plt.legend(loc='upper center')
    
df.drop('review_scores_rating_10', axis=1, inplace=True)

From the distributions we can notice that Montreal and Stockholm have better reviews (in percentage) then Rio de Janeiro.

Geospacial visualization¶

As we have the benefit of geospacial data, would be useful to get a glimpse of the data behavior over maps to maybe find some patterns.

In [7]:
import geopandas as gpd

def read_geo(path):
    f = gpd.read_file(path)
    return f

path = '../sample_data/'
geo = 'geo/'

def read_geos(countries):
    data = {}
    for city in cities:
        file = path + geo + city + '_airbnb.geojson'
        data[city] = gpd.read_file(file)
    return data

geo_df = read_geos(cities)
In [8]:
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame()
for city in cities:
    geo_df[city] = geo_df[city].to_crs({'init': 'epsg:4326'})
    tmp = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df[df.city==city], 
                              geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(df[df.city==city].longitude, 
                                                          df[df.city==city].latitude),
                              crs={'init' :'epsg:4326'})
    sjoined_listings = gpd.sjoin(tmp, geo_df[city], op='within')
    gdf = gdf.append(sjoined_listings)
In [9]:
for city in cities:
    tmp = gdf[gdf.city==city].groupby('index_right').mean().reset_index()
    tmp['num_reviews'] = gdf[gdf.city==city].groupby('index_right').state.size()
    geo_df[city] = geo_df[city].reset_index().merge(tmp, left_on='index', right_on='index_right', how='outer')
In [10]:
def make_poly(df, city, feat, title):
    return gv.Polygons(df[city], vdims=['neighbourhood', feat], label=title).opts(
             color_index=feat, colorbar=True, padding=0.1, tools=['hover'],width=400, height=400,alpha=0.7,
             xaxis=None, yaxis=None)

import panel as pn
import geoviews.tile_sources as gvts

sel_stock = pn.widgets.Select(options=feats)

@pn.depends(basemap=sel_stock)
def stock_view(basemap):
    return tiles*make_poly(geo_df, 'stockholm', basemap, 'Stockholm vis')

pn.Column(sel_stock, stock_view)

CONCLUSIONS¶

On first thought, one could think that one region has better reviews because of the location where better neighborhoods have better reviews. Our visualizations tell other history: high review score areas are sparsely distributed!

Apart from Stockholm where most regions have similar scores, in the other two cities we can observe high scores in neighborhoods surrounded by low score regions.

In Rio, this can be seen clearly in at least three regions: Grumari, Campo dos Afonsos and Turiau. The same behavior can be observed in Montreal at Senneville.

By visualizing the data we can conclude that we need to look further than the simple good/bad regions to find why some reviews are better than others.¶
